# Object Class in Java

## What is Object Class?

In Java, the `Object` class is the parent class of all classes.

- It is present in the `java.lang` package.
- Every Java class directly or indirectly inherits from the `Object` class.
- Because of this, all Java classes can access the methods of the Object class.

### Syntax

```java
public class Object
```

---

# Why Object Class is Important

The Object class provides common functionalities to all Java objects such as:

- Comparing objects
- Converting objects into strings
- Cloning objects
- Getting runtime class information
- Thread communication

---

# Methods of Object Class and Their Purpose

| Method | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `toString()` | Converts object data into string format |
| `equals(Object obj)` | Compares two objects |
| `hashCode()` | Returns hash value of object |
| `getClass()` | Returns runtime class information |
| `clone()` | Creates duplicate copy of object |
| `finalize()` | Called before garbage collection |
| `wait()` | Makes thread wait |
| `wait(long time)` | Waits for specified time |
| `wait(long time, int nanos)` | Waits with nanosecond precision |
| `notify()` | Wakes one waiting thread |
| `notifyAll()` | Wakes all waiting threads |

---

# 1. toString() Method

## Purpose

Used to return string representation of an object.

## Syntax

```java
public String toString()
```

## Example

```java
class Student {
    int id = 101;
    String name = "Mukesh";

    public String toString() {
        return id + " " + name;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student();
        System.out.println(s);
    }
}
```

## Output

```java
101 Mukesh
```

---

# 2. equals() Method

## Purpose

Used to compare two objects.

## Syntax

```java
public boolean equals(Object obj)
```

## Example

```java
class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String s1 = "Java";
        String s2 = "Java";

        System.out.println(s1.equals(s2));
    }
}
```

## Output

```java
true
```

